Poetry and Little-Review Network Analysis

Sophia Juliana Hoeller 5116728

2023-07-17

Introduction:

The “Poetry and the Little Review” Network Analysis aims to examine the relationships between notable modernist authors.

This project is composed by two datasets: a node dataset and an edge dataset.

The nodes csv contains authors, and the edges csv contains weighted publication relationships between those authors, which were calculated based on how many times each author appeared with another author in the same journal issue.

It is an undirect dataset, and so connections between elements have no specific directions, therefore it means that the relationships or interactions between elements are bidirectional or symmetric.

Centrality

It provides measures that quantify the relative importance of nodes based on their structural positions and interactions with other nodes in the network.

There are many measures of centrality. In this project, we’ll examine Degree, Closeness and Betweeness.

1. Degree

The degree of a graph refers to the number of connections/edges that a node has with the other nodes.

Consequently, we check the degree by sorting in a decreasing order, and as we can notice Harriet Monroe has the highest degree.

g_degree = igraph::degree(g)
sort(g_degree, decreasing=TRUE) [1:20]
##          Monroe, Harriet              Pound, Ezra    Anderson, Margaret C. 
##                      256                      146                      141 
##      Henderson, Alice C.         Tietjens, Eunice              Lowell, Amy 
##                      139                      106                      101 
##       Aldington, Richard       Bodenheim, Maxwell       Anderson, Sherwood 
##                       94                       85                       83 
##                       jh     Fletcher, John Gould       Carnevali, Emanuel 
##                       78                       67                       64 
##    Ficke, Arthur Davison               Hecht, Ben             Joyce, James 
##                       61                       59                       57 
##    Foster, George Burman            Soule, George Williams, William Carlos 
##                       56                       55                       55 
##       Kaun, Alexander S.           Bynner, Witter 
##                       54                       50
hist(g_degree, xlab="Degree", main="Histogram of degree distribution", col="violet")

It is evident that the degree distribution is highly skewed to the left, this means that we have many nodes with small degrees. Therefore, we can say that we have an heterogeneous degree distribution.

Then, we plot the graph strength and we can make the same conclusion as before. Graph strength refers to a measure of the influence or importance of a node within a graph or network. It quantifies the extent to which a node affects the flow of information or interactions within the network.

hist(graph.strength(g), xlab="Graph strength", main="Histogram of Graph Strength", col="blueviolet")

plot(g_degree, graph.strength(g), col="deeppink", xlab="Degree", ylab="Graph strength", pch=2, main="Graph Strength vs Degree")

Here, we can observe that degree and graph strength are positively correlated. Higher is the degree of the nodes, higher is the graph strength.

2. Closeness

Closeness is a measure of centrality that quantifies the average distance between a node and all other nodes in the graph.

In our analysis, we can affirm that Harriet Monroe has the highest value, therefore it is the central node.

g_close <-igraph :: closeness(g, mode="total")

Linear vs Poisson Regression

In order to investigate the relationship between the degree distribution of a network and its frequency, we plot two regression models:

  1. A linear regression model where we check if there is a linear association between the log of the degree and the frequency;

  2. A Poisson regression model.

degree_dist <- function (g) {
 fd <- table(igraph::degree(g))
 d <- as.numeric(names(fd)) + 1 
 list(d = d, fd = fd)
}
fd <- degree_distribution(g)
d <- igraph::degree(g)
dd <- degree_dist(g)

(m0 <- lm(log(fd) ~ log(d) , data = dd))
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = log(fd) ~ log(d), data = dd)
## 
## Coefficients:
## (Intercept)       log(d)  
##       4.672       -1.070
(m1 <- glm(fd ~ log(d), family = poisson, data = dd))
## 
## Call:  glm(formula = fd ~ log(d), family = poisson, data = dd)
## 
## Coefficients:
## (Intercept)       log(d)  
##       5.141       -1.190  
## 
## Degrees of Freedom: 54 Total (i.e. Null);  53 Residual
## Null Deviance:       695.8 
## Residual Deviance: 45.49     AIC: 214.3
with(dd, plot(log(d), log(fd), main="Linear regr. vs Poisson log-linear regr."))+abline(m0$coefficients[1], m0$coefficients[2], col = 'purple')+abline(m1$coefficients[1], m1$coefficients[2], col = 'darkgreen')

## integer(0)

It seems that the Poisson model fits better than the Linear, however there is not a clear relationship between node degree and frequency.

We can also use the netstat_dist function in order to analyse the betweenness centrality distribution.

netstat_dist <- function (s, ...) {
  h <- hist(s, plot=FALSE, ...)
  bin_breaks <- as.vector(stats::filter(h$breaks, c(1,1)/2))
  bin_breaks <- bin_breaks[-length(h$breaks)]
  list(s=bin_breaks[h$counts>0], fs=h$counts[h$counts > 0])

}



bd <- netstat_dist(igraph::betweenness(g), breaks = 100) 


(m0 <- lm(log(fs)~log(s), data = bd)) #naive
##

with(bd, plot(log(s), log(fs)))

netstat_dist <- function (s, ...) {
  h <- hist(s, plot = FALSE, ...)
  bin_breaks <- as.vector(stats::filter(h$breaks, c(1, 1) / 2)) 
  bin_breaks <- bin_breaks[-length(h$breaks)]
  list(s = bin_breaks[h$counts > 0], fs = h$counts[h$counts > 0])
}
ds=netstat_dist(graph.strength(g))

gm= glm(fs~log(s), family = poisson, data=ds)
with(ds,plot(log(s), log(fs))); abline(a=gm$coef[1],b=gm$coef[2])

b = igraph::betweenness(g)
s = graph.strength(g)
plot(s,b)

This plot shows the relationship between the betweenness and the strength of the nodes. The nodes that are high, represent that we have numerous connection which are significant.

Graph Structure Analysis

Diameter

It quantifies the maximum distance or number of edges between two nodes.

diam <- diameter(g)
diam
## [1] 10

The resulting number means that the longest path between any two nodes requires a maximum of 10 link.

Mean distance

mean_distance(g)
## [1] 5.408656

It shows the average shortest path length.

Clustering

Clustering is a process that consists on identifying groups of nodes that are more densely connected compared to nodes in other groups.

Transitivity

transitivity(g)
## [1] 0.2237465
hist(transitivity(g, "local"), col="purple", main="Histogram of Transitivity", xlab="Transitivity")

Transitivity is a fundamental concept that measures the tendency of nodes in a network to form triangles or triads.The transitivity coefficient has a range between 0 and 1, where “0” indicates no transitivity and “1” is maximum transitivity.

In this case, the coefficient of transitivity is equal to 0.22, which means that the network is not fully transitive.

Connectivity

It refers to the reachability of a vertex from every other vertex.

igraph::is.connected(g)
## [1] TRUE

This means that there are no isolated nodes or groups of nodes that are not connected to other nodes in the graph.

Motifs

Motifs are subgraphs with a certain well-defined structure that are often through to be “frequently occuring” such as: dyads and triads.

dyad_census(g)
## Warning: `dyad_census()` requires a directed graph.
## $mut
## [1] 2426
## 
## $asym
## [1] 0
## 
## $null
## [1] 73819

We have 2426 pairs with mutual connections and. 73819 pairs with no connection

Triad census is a technique used in network analysis to analyze the distribution and frequencies of different types of triads (three-node subgraphs) within a network. It provides a systematic way to quantify the local connectivity patterns and structural properties of networks.

triad_census(g)
## Warning in triad_census(g): At core/misc/motifs.c:1165 : Triad census called on

ERGM model

Exponential random graph models (ERGM) are models for random graphs which are characterized by the form of their exponential-family distribution.

In an ERGM, the network is represented as a binary adjacency matrix, where each element indicates whether there is a tie or connection between two nodes.

am <- get.adjacency(g, sparse = FALSE)
g1 <- as.network(am, directed = FALSE)
ergm(g1~edges) %>% summary()
## Starting maximum pseudolikelihood estimation (MPLE):
## Obtaining the responsible dyads.
## Evaluating the predictor and response matrix.
## Maximizing the pseudolikelihood.
## Finished MPLE.
## Evaluating log-likelihood at the estimate.
## Call:
## ergm(formula = g1 ~ edges)
## 
## Maximum Likelihood Results:
## 
##       Estimate Std. Error MCMC % z value Pr(>|z|)    
## edges -3.41537    0.02063      0  -165.5   <1e-04 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
##      Null Deviance: 105698  on 76245  degrees of freedom
##  Residual Deviance:  21502  on 76244  degrees of freedom
##  
## AIC: 21504  BIC: 21513  (Smaller is better. MC Std. Err. = 0)

  • The Estimate of the edges is equal to -3.415, this means that the edges have a negative effect on the likelihood.

  • The standard error is 0.02063

  • MCMC % is 0, so it means that the estimation uses the MLE;

  • Pr(\>\|z\|) is very small, therefore it shows a strong evidence against the null hypothesis;

  • AIC and BIC are 21504 and 21513

Therefore, we can conclude that in the ERGM model the edges have a significant negative effect.
